                .c-garfield-summary
                  section.article__summary(aria-label='quick summary')
                    | Skipping servers and using the JAMstack to build and deliver websites and apps can save time, money, and headache by allowing us to deliver only static assets on a CDN. But the trade-off of ditching traditional server-based deployments means that standard approaches to dynamic, asynchronous interactions in our sites and apps aren’t available anymore.
                    br
                    br
                    | Does that mean that JAMstack sites can’t handle dynamic interactions? Definitely not!
                    br
                    br
                    | JAMstack sites are great for creating highly dynamic, asynchronous interactions. With some small adjustments to how we think about our code, we can create fun, immersive interactions using only static assets!
                .drop-caps(aria-hidden='true')
                  img(src='https://d33wubrfki0l68.cloudfront.net/c75c03ae4ee130ff7dae25b82c01373bb2d82dce/c21c0/images/drop-caps/i.svg' alt)
                  img(src='https://d33wubrfki0l68.cloudfront.net/6ea8caf7fa93ed0cf46bc13e25a99da88b43593e/2fd96/images/drop-caps/character-13.svg' alt)
                p
                  | It’s increasingly common to see websites built using the JAMstack — that is, websites that can be served as static HTML files built from JavaScript, Markup, and APIs. Companies love the JAMstack because it reduces infrastructure costs, speeds up delivery, and lowers the barriers for performance and security improvements because shipping static assets removes the need for scaling servers or keeping databases highly available (which also means there are no servers or databases that can be hacked). Developers like the JAMstack because it cuts down on the complexity of getting a website live on the internet: there are no servers to manage or deploy; we can write front-end code and it just
                  em goes live
                  | , like
                  em magic
                  | .
                p
                  | (“Magic” in this case is automated static deployments, which are available for free from a number of companies, including
                  a(href='https://netlify.com/?utm_source=dynamic-jamstack-jl&utm_medium=smashing&utm_campaign=devex') Netlify
                  | , where I work.)
                p But if you spend a lot of time talking to developers about the JAMstack, the question of whether or not the JAMstack can handle Serious Web Applications™ will come up. After all, JAMstack sites are static sites, right? And aren’t static sites super limited in what they can do?
                p This is a really common misconception, and in this article we’re going to dive into where the misconception comes from, look at the capabilities of the JAMstack, and walk through several examples of using the JAMstack to build Serious Web Applications™.
                .c-felix-the-cat
                  h4 JAMstack Fundamentals
                  p
                    | Phil Hawksworth explains what JAMStack actually means and when it makes sense to use it in your projects, as well as how it affects tooling and front-end architecture.
                    a.btn.btn--small.btn--white.btn--white--bordered(href='https://www.smashingmagazine.com/2019/06/jamstack-fundamentals-what-what-how/') Read article →
                .feature-panel-container.hidden(data-component='FeaturePanel' data-audience='non-subscriber' data-remove='true')
                h3#what-makes-a-jamstack-site-static What Makes A JAMstack Site “Static”?
                p Web browsers today load HTML, CSS, and JavaScript files, just like they did back in the 90s.
                p
                  strong A JAMstack site, at its core, is a folder full of HTML, CSS, and JavaScript files.
                p
                  | These are “static assets”, meaning we don’t need an intermediate step to generate them (for example, PHP projects like WordPress need a server to
                  em generate
                  |  the HTML on every request).
                p
                  strong That’s the true power of the JAMstack: it doesn’t require any specialized infrastructure to work.
                  |  You can run a JAMstack site on your local computer, by putting it on your preferred content delivery network (CDN), hosting it with services like GitHub Pages — you can even drag-and-drop the folder into your favorite FTP client to upload it to shared hosting.
                h3#static-assets-don-t-necessarily-mean-static-experiences Static Assets Don’t Necessarily Mean Static Experiences
                p
                  | Because JAMstack sites are made of static files, it’s easy to assume that the experience on those sites is, y’know,
                  em static
                  | . But that’s not the case!
                p JavaScript is capable of doing a whole lot of dynamic stuff. After all, modern JavaScript frameworks are static files after we get through the build step — and there are hundreds of examples of incredibly dynamic website experiences powered by them.
                p There is a common misconception that “static” means inflexible or fixed. But all that “static” really means in the context of “static sites” is that browsers don’t need any help delivering their content — they’re able to use them natively without a server handling a processing step first.
                p Or, put in another way:
                blockquote.pull-quote
                  p
                    a.pull-quote__link(aria-label='Share on Twitter' href='http://twitter.com/share?text=%e2%80%9cStatic%20assets%e2%80%9d%20does%20not%20mean%20static%20apps;%20it%20means%20no%20server%20required.%0a&url=https://smashingmagazine.com%2f2019%2f12%2fdynamic-async-functionality-jamsstack-websites%2f') “Static assets” does not mean static apps; it means no server required.
                  .pull-quote__quotation
                    .pull-quote__bg
                      span.pull-quote__symbol “
                h3#can-the-jamstack-do-that Can The JAMstack Do That?
                p If someone asks about building a new app, it’s common to see suggestions for JAMstack approaches such as Gatsby, Eleventy, Nuxt, and other similar tools. It’s equally common to see objections arise: “static site generators can’t do _______”, where _______ is something dynamic.
                p
                  | But — as we touched on in the previous section — JAMstack sites
                  em can
                  |  handle dynamic content and interactions!
                p Here’s an incomplete list of things that I’ve repeatedly heard people claim the JAMstack can’t handle that it definitely can:
                ul
                  li Load data asynchronously
                  li Handle processing files, such as manipulating images
                  li Read from and write to a database
                  li Handle user authentication and protect content behind a login
                p In the following sections, we’ll look at how to implement each of these workflows on a JAMstack site.
                p
                  | If you can’t wait to see the dynamic JAMstack in action, you can
                  a(href='https://dynamic-jamstack-examples.netlify.com/') check out the demos
                  |  first, then come back and learn how they work.
                blockquote
                  strong A note about the demos
                  | :
                  br
                  br
                  | These demos are written without any frameworks. They are only HTML, CSS, and standard JavaScript. They were built with modern browsers (e.g. Chrome, Firefox, Safari, Edge) in mind and take advantage of newer features like
                  a(href='https://caniuse.com/#feat=es6-module') JavaScript modules
                  | ,
                  a(href='https://caniuse.com/#feat=template') HTML templates
                  | , and the
                  a(href='ttps://caniuse.com/#feat=fetch') Fetch API
                  | . No polyfills were added, so if you’re using an unsupported browser, the demos will probably fail.
                .sponsors__lead-place
                h3#load-data-from-a-third-party-api-asynchronously Load Data From A Third-Party API Asynchronously
                p “What if I need to get new data after my static files are built?”
                p
                  | In the JAMstack, we can take advantage of numerous asynchronous request libraries, including the built-in
                  a(href='https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Fetch_API') Fetch API
                  | , to load data using JavaScript at any point.
                h4#demo-search-a-third-party-api-from-a-jamstack-site Demo: Search A Third-Party API From A JAMstack Site
                p
                  | A common scenario that requires asynchronous loading is when the content we need depends on user input. For example, if we build a search page for the
                  em
                    a(href='https://rickandmortyapi.com/') Rick & Morty API
                  | , we don’t know what content to display until someone has entered a search term.
                p To handle that, we need to:
                ol
                  li Create a form where people can type in their search term,
                  li Listen for a form submission,
                  li Get the search term from the form submission,
                  li Send an asynchronous request to the Rick & Morty API using the search term,
                  li Display the request results on the page.
                p First, we need to create a form and an empty element that will contain our search results, which looks like this:
                pre
                  code.language-html.
                    <form>
                      <label for="name">Find characters by name</label>
                      <input type="text" id="name" name="name" required />
                      <button type="submit">Search</button>
                    </form>

                    <ul id="search-results"></ul>

                p Next, we need to write a function that handles form submissions. This function will:
                ul
                  li Prevent the default form submission behavior
                  li Get the search term from the form input
                  li Use the Fetch API to send a request to the Rick & Morty API using the search term
                  li Call a helper function that displays the search results on the page
                p We also need to add an event listener on the form for the submit event that calls our handler function.
                p Here’s what that code looks like altogether:
                .break-out
                  pre
                    code.language-html.
                      <script type="module">
                       import showResults from './show-results.js';

                       const form = document.querySelector('form');

                       const handleSubmit = async event => {
                         event.preventDefault();

                         // get the search term from the form input
                         const name = form.elements['name'].value;

                         // send a request to the Rick & Morty API based on the user input
                         const characters = await fetch(
                           `https://rickandmortyapi.com/api/character/?name=${name}`,
                         )
                           .then(response => response.json())
                           .catch(error => console.error(error));

                         // add the search results to the DOM
                         showResults(characters.results);
                       };

                       form.addEventListener('submit', handleSubmit);
                      </script>

                p
                  strong Note:
                  |  to stay focused on dynamic JAMstack behaviors, we will not be discussing how utility functions like showResults are written. The code is thoroughly commented, though, so
                  a(href='https://github.com/jlengstorf/dynamic-jamstack-examples/tree/master/examples/01-async-request') check out the source
                  |  to learn how it works!
                p With this code in place, we can load our site in a browser and we’ll see the empty form with no results showing:
                figure.break-out.article__image
                  a(href='https://cloud.netlifyusercontent.com/assets/344dbf88-fdf9-42bb-adb4-46f01eedd629/961f740d-5943-4f7c-a7b1-bba614dbdffd/01-form-empty.png')
                    img(srcset='https://res.cloudinary.com/indysigner/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto/w_400/https://cloud.netlifyusercontent.com/assets/344dbf88-fdf9-42bb-adb4-46f01eedd629/961f740d-5943-4f7c-a7b1-bba614dbdffd/01-form-empty.png 400w, https://res.cloudinary.com/indysigner/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto/w_800/https://cloud.netlifyusercontent.com/assets/344dbf88-fdf9-42bb-adb4-46f01eedd629/961f740d-5943-4f7c-a7b1-bba614dbdffd/01-form-empty.png 800w, https://res.cloudinary.com/indysigner/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto/w_1200/https://cloud.netlifyusercontent.com/assets/344dbf88-fdf9-42bb-adb4-46f01eedd629/961f740d-5943-4f7c-a7b1-bba614dbdffd/01-form-empty.png 1200w, https://res.cloudinary.com/indysigner/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto/w_1600/https://cloud.netlifyusercontent.com/assets/344dbf88-fdf9-42bb-adb4-46f01eedd629/961f740d-5943-4f7c-a7b1-bba614dbdffd/01-form-empty.png 1600w, https://res.cloudinary.com/indysigner/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto/w_2000/https://cloud.netlifyusercontent.com/assets/344dbf88-fdf9-42bb-adb4-46f01eedd629/961f740d-5943-4f7c-a7b1-bba614dbdffd/01-form-empty.png 2000w' src='https://res.cloudinary.com/indysigner/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto/w_400/https://cloud.netlifyusercontent.com/assets/344dbf88-fdf9-42bb-adb4-46f01eedd629/961f740d-5943-4f7c-a7b1-bba614dbdffd/01-form-empty.png' sizes='100vw' alt='Empty search form')
                  figcaption.op-vertical-bottom
                    | The empty search form (
                    a(href='https://cloud.netlifyusercontent.com/assets/344dbf88-fdf9-42bb-adb4-46f01eedd629/961f740d-5943-4f7c-a7b1-bba614dbdffd/01-form-empty.png') Large preview
                    | )
                p If we enter a character name (e.g. “rick”) and click “search”, we see a list of characters whose names contain “rick” displayed:
                figure.break-out.article__image
                  a(href='https://cloud.netlifyusercontent.com/assets/344dbf88-fdf9-42bb-adb4-46f01eedd629/8a69aaf2-6aa7-457b-b6f5-7e317d5d601b/02-search-results.png')
                    img(srcset='https://res.cloudinary.com/indysigner/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto/w_400/https://cloud.netlifyusercontent.com/assets/344dbf88-fdf9-42bb-adb4-46f01eedd629/8a69aaf2-6aa7-457b-b6f5-7e317d5d601b/02-search-results.png 400w, https://res.cloudinary.com/indysigner/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto/w_800/https://cloud.netlifyusercontent.com/assets/344dbf88-fdf9-42bb-adb4-46f01eedd629/8a69aaf2-6aa7-457b-b6f5-7e317d5d601b/02-search-results.png 800w, https://res.cloudinary.com/indysigner/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto/w_1200/https://cloud.netlifyusercontent.com/assets/344dbf88-fdf9-42bb-adb4-46f01eedd629/8a69aaf2-6aa7-457b-b6f5-7e317d5d601b/02-search-results.png 1200w, https://res.cloudinary.com/indysigner/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto/w_1600/https://cloud.netlifyusercontent.com/assets/344dbf88-fdf9-42bb-adb4-46f01eedd629/8a69aaf2-6aa7-457b-b6f5-7e317d5d601b/02-search-results.png 1600w, https://res.cloudinary.com/indysigner/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto/w_2000/https://cloud.netlifyusercontent.com/assets/344dbf88-fdf9-42bb-adb4-46f01eedd629/8a69aaf2-6aa7-457b-b6f5-7e317d5d601b/02-search-results.png 2000w' src='https://res.cloudinary.com/indysigner/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto/w_400/https://cloud.netlifyusercontent.com/assets/344dbf88-fdf9-42bb-adb4-46f01eedd629/8a69aaf2-6aa7-457b-b6f5-7e317d5d601b/02-search-results.png' sizes='100vw' alt='Search form filled with “rick” with characters named “Rick” displayed below.')
                  figcaption.op-vertical-bottom
                    | We see search results after the form is filled out. (
                    a(href='https://cloud.netlifyusercontent.com/assets/344dbf88-fdf9-42bb-adb4-46f01eedd629/8a69aaf2-6aa7-457b-b6f5-7e317d5d601b/02-search-results.png') Large preview
                    | )
                p Hey! Did that static site just dynamically load data? Holy buckets!
                p
                  | You can try this out for yourself on the
                  a(href='https://dynamic-jamstack-examples.netlify.com/01-async-request/') live demo
                  | , or
                  a(href='https://github.com/jlengstorf/dynamic-jamstack-examples/tree/master/examples/01-async-request') check out the full source code
                  |  for more details.
                h3#handle-expensive-computing-tasks-off-the-user-s-device Handle Expensive Computing Tasks Off the User’s Device
                p
                  | In many apps, we need to do things that are pretty resource-intensive, such as processing an image. While some of these kinds of operations are
                  em possible
                  |  using client-side JavaScript only, it’s not necessarily a great idea to make your users’ devices do all that work. If they’re on a low-powered device or trying to stretch out their last 5% of battery life, making their device do a bunch of work is probably going to be a frustrating experience for them.
                p So does that mean that JAMstack apps are out of luck? Not at all!
                p The “A” in JAMstack stands for APIs. This means we can send off that work to an API and avoid spinning our users’ computer fans up to the “hover” setting.
                p “But wait,” you might say. “If our app needs to do custom work, and that work requires an API, doesn’t that just mean we’re building a server?”
                p Thanks to the power of serverless functions, we don’t have to!
                p Serverless functions (also called “lambda functions”) are a sort of API without any server boilerplate required. We get to write a plain old JavaScript function, and all of the work of deploying, scaling, routing, and so on is offloaded to our serverless provider of choice.
                blockquote.pull-quote
                  p
                    a.pull-quote__link(aria-label='Share on Twitter' href='http://twitter.com/share?text=Using%20serverless%20functions%20doesn%e2%80%99t%20mean%20there%e2%80%99s%20not%20a%20server;%20it%20just%20means%20that%20we%20don%e2%80%99t%20need%20to%20think%20about%20a%20server.%0a&url=https://smashingmagazine.com%2f2019%2f12%2fdynamic-async-functionality-jamsstack-websites%2f') Using serverless functions doesn’t mean there’s not a server; it just means that we don’t need to think about a server.
                  .pull-quote__quotation
                    .pull-quote__bg
                      span.pull-quote__symbol “
                p Serverless functions are the peanut butter to our JAMstack: they unlock a whole world of high-powered, dynamic functionality without ever asking us to deal with server code or devops.
                h4#demo-convert-an-image-to-grayscale Demo: Convert An Image To Grayscale
                p Let’s assume we have an app that needs to:
                ul
                  li Download an image from a URL
                  li Convert that image to grayscale
                  li Upload the converted image to a GitHub repo
                p As far as I know, there’s no way to do image conversions like that entirely in the browser — and even if there was, it’s a fairly resource-intensive thing to do, so we probably don’t want to put that load on our users’ devices.
                p Instead, we can submit the URL to be converted to a serverless function, which will do the heavy lifting for us and send back a URL to a converted image.
                p
                  | For our serverless function, we’ll be using
                  a(href='https://www.netlify.com/products/functions/?utm_source=dynamic-jamstack-jl&utm_medium=smashingmag&utm_campaign=devex') Netlify Functions
                  | . In our site’s code, we add a folder at the root level called “functions” and create a new file called “convert-image.js” inside. Then we write what’s called a handler, which is what receives and — as you may have guessed —
                  em handles
                  |  requests to our serverless function.
                .sponsors__lead-place
                p To convert an image, it looks like this:
                pre
                  code.language-javascript.
                    exports.handler = async event => {
                     // only try to handle POST requests
                     if (event.httpMethod !== 'POST') {
                       return { statusCode: 404, body: '404 Not Found' };
                     }

                     try {
                       // get the image URL from the POST submission
                       const { imageURL } = JSON.parse(event.body);

                       // use a temporary directory to avoid intermediate file cruft
                       // see https://www.npmjs.com/package/tmp
                       const tmpDir = tmp.dirSync();

                       const convertedPath = await convertToGrayscale(imageURL, tmpDir);

                       // upload the processed image to GitHub
                       const response = await uploadToGitHub(convertedPath, tmpDir.name);

                       return {
                         statusCode: 200,
                         body: JSON.stringify({
                           url: response.data.content.download_url,
                         }),
                       };
                     } catch (error) {
                       return {
                         statusCode: 500,
                         body: JSON.stringify(error.message),
                       };
                     }
                    };

                p This function does the following:
                ol
                  li Checks to make sure the request was sent using the HTTP POST method
                  li Grabs the image URL from the POST body
                  li Creates a temporary directory for storing files that will be cleaned up once the function is done executing
                  li Calls a helper function that converts the image to grayscale
                  li Calls a helper function that uploads the converted image to GitHub
                  li Returns a response object with an HTTP 200 status code and the newly uploaded image’s URL
